ri(\\\"https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2\\\")\\n                metadataSources {\\n                    artifact()\\n                }\\n            }\\n        }\\n        filter {\\n            includeModule(\\\"jakarta.websocket\\\", \\\"jakarta.websocket-api\\\")\\n            includeModule(\\\"jakarta.websocket\\\", \\\"jakarta.websocket-client-api\\\")\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\\ndependencies {\\n\"}]}\n3583:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring Gradle configurations**\\n\\nI'm considering how to configure repositories in the project build.gradle, particularly around mavenCentral and its metadata sources. If a repository is already added, can I clear and re-add it? I think I should clear existing repositories and then set up mavenLocal and mavenCentral with artifact metadata. But oh, what if mavenLocal also has a broken POM? Direct dependencies may not parse correctly without POMs either. I'll also look into using exclusive content for the jakarta.websocket group. Does that apply here?\\n\\n**Patch Gradle configurations**\\n\\nI think focusing on using only an artifact repository for jakarta.websocket might help. It seems standard to avoid mavenCentral for that group. If mavenCentral is also present, then exclusiveContent could restrict searches, right? The docs suggest that it declares the repository to exclusively contain the group. I wonder if the resolutionStrategy for eachDependency could come into play here. I might need to patch the build.gradle, ensuring it only allows additional dependencies if absolutely required. I just need to confirm those dependencies don’t trigger POM parsing — that’s essential!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02025de4422f0e35016a2368157f748193b3e83856a101f54d\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"content\\\":[],\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqI2ghQLKi8Etd6hyO7qLwTaDGiXbHs0xeqWa4l3_9sX3GkXWtDBcsJCmagj0